WEBVTT

00:01.376 --> 00:03.587
[ "On Top" plays ]

00:03.587 --> 00:05.547
Oh, sorry.
Visitors can't park down here.

00:05.547 --> 00:06.840
I‐I know.
I'm not.

00:06.840 --> 00:08.175
My dad sent me down
to his car

00:08.175 --> 00:09.718
to get the coffees
he bought for us.

00:09.718 --> 00:11.011
Oh.
Who's your dad?

00:11.011 --> 00:12.387
Steve Miller.
Property Crimes?

00:12.387 --> 00:14.389
[ Chuckles ] Yeah.
T‐That's him.

00:14.389 --> 00:16.099
We don't, uh, get to see
each other too often

00:16.099 --> 00:17.267
since the divorce.

00:17.267 --> 00:19.186
Mom got full custody.

00:19.186 --> 00:21.939
So he makes me stop by
the station

00:21.939 --> 00:24.775
for some "father‐son"
coffee time before school.

00:24.775 --> 00:26.235
Oh. That's nice.

00:26.235 --> 00:28.111
[ Chuckles ]

00:28.111 --> 00:29.571
[ Elevator bell dings ]
After you.

00:29.571 --> 00:31.573
Thanks.

00:31.573 --> 00:33.617
♪ Don't care what you say ♪

00:33.617 --> 00:35.911
Four, right?
Huh?

00:35.911 --> 00:37.287
Property Crimes?
Four?

00:37.287 --> 00:40.207
Uh, yeah. Yeah.
Thanks.

00:41.959 --> 00:43.710
Yeah.
Divorce is tough.

00:43.710 --> 00:46.755
I have a son a few years older
than you.

00:46.755 --> 00:49.091
I remember when his mom and I
split up,

00:49.091 --> 00:51.468
I wanted to do everything
I could just to show him

00:51.468 --> 00:53.929
that I would still
be there for him.

00:53.929 --> 00:56.556
You know, still be Dad.

00:56.556 --> 00:59.559
I'm sure your father's just
trying to do the same for you.

00:59.559 --> 01:00.894
Yeah. [ Sighs ]

01:00.894 --> 01:02.771
And this is my stop.

01:02.771 --> 01:04.648
[ Elevator bell dings ]
Nice to meet you.

01:04.648 --> 01:06.483
Uh, you, too.

01:06.483 --> 01:08.026
Oh.

01:08.026 --> 01:10.320
Just wanted to say
thank you for the pep talk.

01:10.320 --> 01:12.322
I ‐‐ I needed it.

01:12.322 --> 01:13.991
No problem.

01:13.991 --> 01:16.827
♪♪

01:16.827 --> 01:19.413
[ Indistinct conversations ]

01:22.833 --> 01:25.085
Lucy: We need to figure out
how he got access to the roof.

01:25.085 --> 01:27.004
Okay.

01:27.004 --> 01:28.839
Hey.
What's happening?

01:28.839 --> 01:30.507
Someone stole
a police helicopter.

01:30.507 --> 01:31.883
What?
Sgt. Grey: Nolan.

01:31.883 --> 01:33.468
Sir, I just heard about
the airship.

01:33.468 --> 01:34.970
Do you know
who took it?
No.

01:34.970 --> 01:36.221
But you do.

01:38.807 --> 01:42.519
♪ Whoa, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh,
whoa, oh, oh ♪

01:42.519 --> 01:47.899
♪ I'm gonna win for you
like I know you want me to do ♪

01:47.899 --> 01:50.610
Airship Three,
I repeat, do you copy?

01:53.655 --> 01:56.533
Sir, in Nolan's defense,
a teenager stealing

01:56.533 --> 01:59.453
a police helicopter ‐‐
it's highly unexpected behavior.

01:59.453 --> 02:00.704
We're cops.

02:00.704 --> 02:03.040
"Highly unexpected"
is what we do before breakfast.

02:03.040 --> 02:04.541
Hey, kid,
I know you can hear me.

02:04.541 --> 02:07.169
See, right now I have the FBI,
Homeland Security,

02:07.169 --> 02:09.546
and the DOD
blowing up my phone,

02:09.546 --> 02:11.173
and they're all saying
the same thing ‐‐

02:11.173 --> 02:13.884
we should launch fighter jets
and blow you out of the sky.

02:13.884 --> 02:15.594
Now, do you copy?

02:15.594 --> 02:18.472
This is Airship Three.
Please identify yourself.

02:20.432 --> 02:23.018
Sergeant Wade Grey, LAPD.

02:23.018 --> 02:24.269
'Sup, Wade?
Listen, I know

02:24.269 --> 02:25.854
<i>they're not gonna blow me</i>
<i>out of the sky</i>

02:25.854 --> 02:27.773
<i>while I'm over</i>
<i>a populated area,</i>

02:27.773 --> 02:29.191
so tell them to just save
the jet fuel, okay?

02:29.191 --> 02:32.069
This is a joy ride,
not DEFCON 1.

02:32.069 --> 02:33.654
I'm just gonna have
a little fun.

02:33.654 --> 02:35.364
I'll return your helicopter
good as new.

02:35.364 --> 02:37.157
Listen here, boy, I ‐‐
If I may.

02:40.327 --> 02:43.538
Hey. This is John Nolan,
from the elevator.

02:43.538 --> 02:45.248
Hey! Yeah, yeah.
The divorced dad.

02:45.248 --> 02:48.001
<i>Look, you are super good</i>
<i>at bonding, by the way.</i>

02:48.001 --> 02:50.879
<i>I mean, I‐I really felt</i>
<i>the emotional connection.</i>

02:50.879 --> 02:52.798
Yes. Thank you.

02:52.798 --> 02:56.009
Listen, we know Steve Miller's
not really your father,

02:56.009 --> 02:57.344
so why don't you tell us
who you really are

02:57.344 --> 02:58.929
and what you want?

02:58.929 --> 03:02.182
<i>Who I really am</i>
<i>is the hero of my own story.</i>

03:02.182 --> 03:05.519
<i>And what I want is to</i>
<i>complete the hero's journey.</i>

03:05.519 --> 03:06.937
<i>Whoa!</i>

03:06.937 --> 03:08.480
What is it?
What happened?

03:08.480 --> 03:10.982
[ Suspenseful music plays ]

03:10.982 --> 03:14.486
<i>I just saw a cyclist almost get</i>
<i>demolished by a vehicle.</i>

03:14.486 --> 03:16.697
<i>I mean, this city really needs</i>
<i>to add more bike lanes.</i>

03:16.697 --> 03:19.116
<i>But, hey, look, this has been</i>
<i>fun, but I gotta go</i>

03:19.116 --> 03:21.702
<i>because flying a real</i>
<i>helicopter is a lot harder</i>

03:21.702 --> 03:23.453
<i>than the video‐game simulation</i>
<i>made it seem.</i>

03:23.453 --> 03:25.330
<i>So, we'll talk soon, okay?</i>

03:25.330 --> 03:27.499
No, no, wait,
wait, wait.

03:27.499 --> 03:28.792
Hero?
[ Sighs ]

03:28.792 --> 03:31.086
Okay, uh,
do we believe him?

03:31.086 --> 03:33.880
I mean, he seemed like
a sweet kid on the elevator.

03:33.880 --> 03:35.298
He's not talking like
he's planning on

03:35.298 --> 03:36.675
doing anything violent.

03:36.675 --> 03:38.385
And he's right.
They won't shoot him down

03:38.385 --> 03:39.928
unless he poses
an imminent threat.

03:39.928 --> 03:42.764
So, how do we get him down
with no casualties?

03:42.764 --> 03:44.516
We got four hours
to figure that out.

03:44.516 --> 03:46.393
That's how much fuel
he's got left.

03:46.393 --> 03:49.521
Nolan, get out there and
shadow him the best you can.

03:49.521 --> 03:51.815
Can I take Lucy with me?
She'll help me get in his head.

03:51.815 --> 03:53.608
Okay. Good idea.

03:53.608 --> 03:56.778
And, Nolan, get him to land
before gravity does it for him.

03:56.778 --> 03:58.655
Yes, sir.

03:58.655 --> 04:01.658
♪♪

04:01.658 --> 04:03.452
Hey. You ready to roll?

04:03.452 --> 04:05.996
Oh. Actually, Grey assigned me
to ride with Nolan

04:05.996 --> 04:07.289
to trail helicopter kid.

04:07.289 --> 04:08.540
Alright. Let me know
if you need anything.

04:08.540 --> 04:10.000
Mm‐hmm.

04:11.460 --> 04:13.879
Hey. Guess who's sitting
in a holding cell right now?

04:13.879 --> 04:15.255
Yeah.
I don't do guessing games.

04:15.255 --> 04:16.882
Your old friend,
Dez Robinson.

04:16.882 --> 04:18.925
What'd he do?
Cabot and Lodge
pulled him over

04:18.925 --> 04:20.177
for a traffic violation.

04:20.177 --> 04:22.262
They found a diamond bracelet
in his car that was taken

04:22.262 --> 04:24.389
during a home invasion
that left a family dead.

04:24.389 --> 04:25.807
That triple murder
in Larchmont Village?

04:25.807 --> 04:27.601
Yeah. I'm about to go
question him. You want in?

04:27.601 --> 04:29.269
Bet your ass I do.

04:29.269 --> 04:31.104
I'm surprised you've stayed out
of prison for this long,

04:31.104 --> 04:32.856
given that you're dumb enough
to drive around

04:32.856 --> 04:35.567
with stolen property
when you're still on probation.

04:35.567 --> 04:39.154
The bracelet was stolen?
I had no idea.

04:39.154 --> 04:40.655
I‐I bought it
from a pawnshop

04:40.655 --> 04:42.574
to give to my mother
for her ‐‐ her birthday.

04:42.574 --> 04:46.077
Yeah, which pawnshop?
[ Sighs ] Man,
I don't remember that.

04:46.077 --> 04:48.580
I went to like nine of them
[chuckles] you know,

04:48.580 --> 04:50.916
looking for
the perfect gift.

04:50.916 --> 04:53.001
I love my mom.
Do you have the receipt?

04:53.001 --> 04:54.586
No.
I don't believe in them.

04:54.586 --> 04:57.756
Thing is, Dez, that bracelet
wasn't just stolen.

04:57.756 --> 04:59.841
It was taken from
a home invasion two nights ago,

04:59.841 --> 05:01.301
where three people
were killed.

05:01.301 --> 05:02.552
And we believe the same crew
is responsible

05:02.552 --> 05:04.387
for two other home invasion
murders.

05:04.387 --> 05:05.889
Oh, wow.
You guys really
don't like

05:05.889 --> 05:07.182
to leave any witnesses,
do you?

05:07.182 --> 05:08.767
I don't know
what you're talking about.

05:08.767 --> 05:11.353
Really. I‐I was at work
two nights ago.

05:12.229 --> 05:13.438
Just check with my boss.

05:13.438 --> 05:15.565
Oh, I will.

05:15.565 --> 05:17.734
Look, Dez...

05:17.734 --> 05:21.738
you and I ‐‐
we go way back, right?

05:21.738 --> 05:23.198
The joy of recidivism.

05:23.198 --> 05:25.867
And while you've never been
afraid of a little violence,

05:25.867 --> 05:27.577
you're not a killer.

05:27.577 --> 05:30.539
So I don't think you'd shoot
that family in cold blood.

05:30.539 --> 05:32.499
No. I think you hooked up
with this crew

05:32.499 --> 05:34.876
not knowing they were killers,
and now you're tied to them.

05:34.876 --> 05:37.128
If you tell us who they are,
we can make a deal.

05:37.128 --> 05:39.381
If not, we hang the murders
around your neck

05:39.381 --> 05:41.591
with the rest of your crew,
and you'll die in prison.

05:41.591 --> 05:43.051
All we need is a name.

05:43.051 --> 05:47.264
♪♪

05:47.264 --> 05:48.807
Adrienne Mount.

05:48.807 --> 05:51.142
Adrienne Mount
committed the murders?

05:51.142 --> 05:53.270
No.
She's my lawyer.

05:53.270 --> 05:55.605
I'd like to
talk to her, please.

05:55.605 --> 05:57.065
Harper:
Are you wearing makeup?

05:57.065 --> 06:00.610
What?
[ Chuckling ] No.

06:00.610 --> 06:02.279
Okay, yeah.

06:02.279 --> 06:05.198
Um...I thought that
I got that off.

06:05.198 --> 06:07.242
Hmm.
Yeah. We had
a late‐night shoot

06:07.242 --> 06:11.079
at Club Avalon
for my reality show pilot.

06:11.079 --> 06:13.707
How exactly does partying
at a nightclub

06:13.707 --> 06:15.500
reset the world's image
of you?

06:15.500 --> 06:16.710
Well, no.
We were, like, you know,

06:16.710 --> 06:18.253
shooting the reenactments
of, like,

06:18.253 --> 06:20.005
what my life was like
before the murder.

06:20.005 --> 06:21.756
Which, actually,
was pretty cool.

06:21.756 --> 06:23.300
Listen, Hollywood,

06:23.300 --> 06:25.051
I will put up with
this reality show

06:25.051 --> 06:27.345
as long as it helps
to clear your name.

06:27.345 --> 06:30.140
But if it starts to affect
your performance ‐‐

06:30.140 --> 06:31.600
It won't, okay?
I swear.

06:31.600 --> 06:33.852
And, look, I couldn't be
any less "Hollywood."

06:33.852 --> 06:35.979
Kenton: Mr. Thorsen.
Good morning, sir.

06:35.979 --> 06:37.480
I got you
your breakfast.

06:37.480 --> 06:39.149
Who are you?

06:39.149 --> 06:40.775
Kenton Scott,
Mr. Thorsen's assistant.

06:40.775 --> 06:42.986
Uh, no.

06:42.986 --> 06:45.280
I mean, yes, but he's only
supposed to be assisting me

06:45.280 --> 06:46.489
when I'm working on
the show.

06:46.489 --> 06:48.158
And right now,
I'm at my real job.

06:48.158 --> 06:49.492
And I'm still
on probation,

06:49.492 --> 06:51.578
so I need you to go now,
okay?

06:51.578 --> 06:53.246
No.

06:53.246 --> 06:54.664
W‐What do you mean, no?
You work for me.

06:54.664 --> 06:56.291
Uh, technically,
I work for your mother.

06:56.291 --> 06:59.169
And she...scares the hell
outta me.

06:59.169 --> 07:01.338
I‐In the best way.
She's amazing. I love her.

07:01.338 --> 07:03.590
But if I make a mistake, she'll
catapult me into the sun,

07:03.590 --> 07:05.884
so I'm here for you
24/7.

07:05.884 --> 07:08.428
So should I ride with you,
or just follow in my car?

07:08.428 --> 07:09.804
Probably my car,
so I can run errands if you ‐‐

07:09.804 --> 07:12.682
Kenton, Kenton, Kenton,
take a breath.

07:12.682 --> 07:15.518
Okay? Uh, assistants
get lunch, right?

07:15.518 --> 07:16.936
Yes. Absolutely.

07:16.936 --> 07:20.065
Okay. I'm having
this wild pregnancy craving

07:20.065 --> 07:21.983
for some, uh,
bulgogi tacos.

07:21.983 --> 07:23.318
Great, I'm sure I can find that
around here ‐‐

07:23.318 --> 07:25.236
Yeah. But not just
any bulgogi tacos.

07:25.236 --> 07:28.281
They have to be from
Apollo Yang's food truck,

07:28.281 --> 07:30.659
which is parked at
a different location every day.

07:30.659 --> 07:33.119
And the only way
to obtain that location

07:33.119 --> 07:35.246
is to text
a secret password

07:35.246 --> 07:39.292
to a specific short code,
which...I don't have.

07:39.292 --> 07:40.669
♪♪

07:40.669 --> 07:41.961
On it.

07:43.254 --> 07:44.631
Yeah.
That'll keep him busy.

07:44.631 --> 07:46.466
I'm so sorry. That ‐‐
That won't happen again.

07:46.466 --> 07:47.801
I'mma talk to my mom
about that, okay?

07:47.801 --> 07:49.302
Mm‐hmm.

07:49.302 --> 07:51.096
You alright?
Yeah. I think so.

07:51.096 --> 07:53.890
I just got uncomfortable
all of a sudden.

07:53.890 --> 07:55.392
It's the baby?
I don't know.

07:55.392 --> 07:58.812
Um, maybe we should,
um, stop by my OB's office

07:58.812 --> 08:01.064
at the hospital,
just to make sure.

08:01.064 --> 08:02.440
Okay.

08:02.440 --> 08:05.193
Alright.
[ Exhales deeply ]

08:05.193 --> 08:12.575
♪♪

08:12.575 --> 08:14.744
[ Beeping ]
Oh. They ID'd 'copter kid.

08:14.744 --> 08:16.788
Leo Thomas, age 17.

08:16.788 --> 08:17.914
No priors.

08:17.914 --> 08:18.957
Grey's reaching out
to the family.

08:18.957 --> 08:20.750
Clearly,
there's trouble there.

08:20.750 --> 08:23.253
Well‐adjusted kids don't steal
police helicopters.

08:23.253 --> 08:24.546
I mean, it could
be classic

08:24.546 --> 08:26.381
teenage attention‐seeking
behavior.

08:26.381 --> 08:28.466
You know, trying to stand out,
establish their identity.

08:28.466 --> 08:30.093
The whole thing's gotten
exponentially worse

08:30.093 --> 08:31.594
since social media.

08:31.594 --> 08:34.222
Dying your hair is classic
attention seeking.

08:34.222 --> 08:37.392
Stealing a police helicopter
is extremely dangerous.

08:37.392 --> 08:39.978
Teenagers don't have
fully formed brains.

08:39.978 --> 08:42.355
They don't perceive risk
in the same ways that we do.

08:42.355 --> 08:43.690
You remember that age.

08:43.690 --> 08:45.108
I remember working
two part‐time jobs

08:45.108 --> 08:47.444
to save up for college.
You never acted out?

08:47.444 --> 08:49.237
Not in
any substantial way.

08:49.237 --> 08:50.864
Well ‐‐ [ Sighs ]

08:50.864 --> 08:52.782
You know, I don't know why
I'm surprised.

08:52.782 --> 08:54.534
Oh, like you were
such a rebel.

08:54.534 --> 08:58.288
I'm ‐‐ [ Chuckles ]
You have no idea.

08:58.288 --> 09:02.333
[ Cellphone ringing ]

09:02.333 --> 09:04.419
Hello?
How's Harper doing?

09:04.419 --> 09:05.670
Still waiting to hear,
sir,

09:05.670 --> 09:07.047
but the doctor
didn't seem worried.

09:07.047 --> 09:09.299
Good.
Keep me updated.

09:09.299 --> 09:11.384
In the meantime, I have
an assignment for you.

09:11.384 --> 09:12.969
Yes, sir.

09:12.969 --> 09:14.596
A riot broke out at
Men's Correctional this morning.

09:14.596 --> 09:17.474
<i>There were dozens injured and</i>
<i>one prisoner airlifted to Shaw</i>

09:17.474 --> 09:20.685
for emergency surgery ‐‐
Langston Bryant.

09:20.685 --> 09:23.104
So I need you to relieve
the sheriff's deputy

09:23.104 --> 09:24.230
that accompanied him.

09:24.230 --> 09:25.732
<i>And, Thorsen ‐‐</i>
Sir?

09:25.732 --> 09:28.485
Langston's 18 years into
a life sentence

09:28.485 --> 09:29.736
for killing a cop

09:29.736 --> 09:31.446
<i>for a routine</i>
<i>traffic stop.</i>

09:31.446 --> 09:33.615
<i>He did it once, he could</i>
<i>certainly do it again.</i>

09:33.615 --> 09:34.866
Watch yourself.

09:34.866 --> 09:36.242
Yes, sir.

09:36.242 --> 09:38.203
Woman:
<i>Nurse Howard to 2 West, please.</i>

09:38.203 --> 09:40.914
Aaron: Hey, I'm here
to relieve you.

09:40.914 --> 09:43.166
Great. I gotta get back
to the prison.

09:43.166 --> 09:45.043
Damn, man,
are you okay?

09:45.043 --> 09:47.796
[ Chuckles ]
Not even close.

09:47.796 --> 09:50.757
The prisoner in there ‐‐
he's as dangerous as they come,

09:50.757 --> 09:53.384
so be smart.

09:53.384 --> 09:55.553
Yes, sir.
I've been briefed.

09:55.553 --> 10:04.104
♪♪

10:04.104 --> 10:07.774
Good morning, Los Angeles!

10:07.774 --> 10:11.528
This is Airship Three coming to
you live and in the sky.

10:11.528 --> 10:13.696
Looks like there's gonna be
traffic on...

10:13.696 --> 10:15.156
all of the roads.

10:15.156 --> 10:16.491
And I'm actually taking a poll

10:16.491 --> 10:18.451
about where I should go
patrol next.

10:18.451 --> 10:21.121
Um, you know, I‐I could take
a trip over to Santa Monica,

10:21.121 --> 10:23.414
maybe see what'll be underwater
when all the glaciers melt.

10:23.414 --> 10:25.125
Hey, there, Leo.
Divorced Dad here.

10:25.125 --> 10:27.210
How's it going up there?
Me? Can't complain.

10:27.210 --> 10:28.920
You know where the bathroom is
in this thing?

10:28.920 --> 10:32.966
Listen, Leo ‐‐ what you are
doing is really dangerous.

10:32.966 --> 10:35.385
Your family is worried sick
about you.

10:35.385 --> 10:37.262
Yeah,
that's not gonna work

10:37.262 --> 10:38.930
and I'm disappointed
you thought it would.

10:38.930 --> 10:40.306
<i>So, see ya.</i>

10:40.306 --> 10:42.976
Look. Wait. Hang on.
Hang on. Hang on. Just ‐‐

10:42.976 --> 10:45.228
Did you really learn to fly
from video games?

10:45.228 --> 10:48.273
And a few
ClipTalk tutorials.

10:48.273 --> 10:51.568
Ugh.
Wow. That's ‐‐

10:51.568 --> 10:53.236
Hats off, man. Wow.
I mean, I ‐‐

10:53.236 --> 10:55.989
I love me some video games,
but that's ‐‐

10:55.989 --> 10:57.574
You know, uh,
"Breath of the Wild"

10:57.574 --> 10:59.993
consumed my life
for about four months.

10:59.993 --> 11:03.204
I beat Ganon ‐‐ twice.
<i>Impressive.</i>

11:03.204 --> 11:05.456
I‐I bet you're feeling a little
bit like Link and his glider,

11:05.456 --> 11:07.167
flying around up there,
don't you?

11:07.167 --> 11:08.585
A little, yeah.

11:08.585 --> 11:10.920
But even Link couldn't fly
forever, right?

11:10.920 --> 11:13.506
He had to land sometime,
save Zelda, right?

11:13.506 --> 11:16.593
That's right.
The hero always has a purpose.

11:16.593 --> 11:19.554
Great. We're gonna find you
a nice, open place to land.

11:19.554 --> 11:22.473
<i>And he can also use help</i>
<i>from his allies.</i>

11:22.473 --> 11:24.058
Are you an ally,
Mr. Nolan?

11:26.811 --> 11:28.062
Yes, I am.

11:28.062 --> 11:29.355
<i>Great.</i>
<i>So here's the deal.</i>

11:29.355 --> 11:33.651
In order to help me complete
my hero's journey...

11:33.651 --> 11:35.403
I need you to complete
three quests.

11:36.696 --> 11:39.449
If you succeed,
I'll give myself up.

11:45.121 --> 11:46.581
This is not
a video game, Leo.

11:46.581 --> 11:47.999
No.
It's something deeper.

11:47.999 --> 11:50.293
Games, fantasy novels,
they're all built on

11:50.293 --> 11:53.796
the same architecture ‐‐
the hero's journey.

11:53.796 --> 11:56.674
<i>A universal story</i>
<i>so central to our identities,</i>

11:56.674 --> 11:58.384
<i>it's as if it's written</i>
<i>in our DNA.</i>

11:58.384 --> 12:00.345
He's been reading
Joseph Campbell.
Ah.

12:00.345 --> 12:03.097
You're the mentor ‐‐
an older, wiser figure

12:03.097 --> 12:05.600
like an Obi‐Wan
or a Dumbledore.

12:05.600 --> 12:08.603
They usually die towards
the end...
[ Scoffs ]

12:08.603 --> 12:10.521
...to signify the hero's true
coming into himself.

12:10.521 --> 12:12.148
Who knows?
Maybe you'll pull through.

12:12.148 --> 12:13.691
Leo, this isn't a myth.

12:13.691 --> 12:17.695
This is real life,
and you are in real danger.

12:17.695 --> 12:20.114
I can't play along with
this quest nonsense.

12:20.114 --> 12:21.491
Why not?

12:21.491 --> 12:22.992
Why not slay dragons
for a kid

12:22.992 --> 12:26.037
I think is
increasingly delusional?

12:26.037 --> 12:28.414
Look, often the best way ‐‐
the only way

12:28.414 --> 12:31.668
to deal with people
who are in a crisis situation

12:31.668 --> 12:33.962
is to accept
their reality.

12:33.962 --> 12:36.130
I mean, it's either this
or we drive around all day,

12:36.130 --> 12:37.548
looking up.

12:40.551 --> 12:43.304
Alright.
What are the quests?

12:43.304 --> 12:45.098
I'm not gonna give you
all of them up front.

12:45.098 --> 12:46.349
It doesn't work that way.

12:48.476 --> 12:49.727
What do we have
to lose?

12:49.727 --> 12:51.771
Lives?
A helicopter?

12:54.232 --> 12:56.776
Fine. What is
the first quest?

12:56.776 --> 13:01.447
♪♪

13:01.447 --> 13:03.241
Okay. 9412 Orange.

13:03.241 --> 13:04.742
It's been empty
for over a year.

13:04.742 --> 13:08.913
Persistent 911 calls
about drug activity.

13:08.913 --> 13:10.248
Let's take a look.

13:10.248 --> 13:12.333
♪♪

13:12.333 --> 13:14.627
<i>This is a quest</i>
<i>based in tragedy.</i>

13:14.627 --> 13:16.004
<i>A bunch of kids from my school,</i>

13:16.004 --> 13:18.339
<i>they started hanging out</i>
<i>at this abandoned house.</i>

13:18.339 --> 13:20.133
<i>They party, make a mess ‐‐</i>

13:20.133 --> 13:21.676
<i>just the typical rebellion</i>
<i>of youth.</i>

13:21.676 --> 13:25.138
And some hardcore guys saw
a market and they moved in.

13:25.138 --> 13:28.433
<i>They started selling</i>
<i>some hardcore drugs,</i>

13:28.433 --> 13:33.271
and a raven‐haired girl
OD'd.

13:33.271 --> 13:37.859
A young princess the hero
liked from afar.

13:37.859 --> 13:39.360
<i>You can't save the princess,</i>

13:39.360 --> 13:41.362
<i>but you can stop the monsters</i>
<i>who hurt her.</i>

13:41.362 --> 13:42.613
[ Knock on door ]

13:46.701 --> 13:47.702
♪ Run ♪

13:47.702 --> 13:48.953
Running!

13:48.953 --> 13:51.956
♪♪

13:51.956 --> 13:53.374
♪ Run ♪

13:53.374 --> 13:57.045
♪♪

13:57.045 --> 13:58.504
♪ Run ♪

13:58.504 --> 14:01.090
♪ I got 'em, I got 'em,
I got 'em, I got 'em ♪

14:01.090 --> 14:02.341
♪ I got 'em, I got 'em ♪

14:02.341 --> 14:03.843
Turn around.

14:03.843 --> 14:05.136
Put your hands on your head,
fingers interlaced.

14:05.136 --> 14:07.680
Don't move.

14:07.680 --> 14:09.140
♪ Can't stop, not yet ♪

14:09.140 --> 14:10.391
You got him?
Yeah.

14:10.391 --> 14:11.851
♪ Never rest
till I'm in the safe zone ♪

14:11.851 --> 14:12.977
♪ I know I can make it home ♪

14:12.977 --> 14:14.187
♪ Can't breathe, next week ♪

14:14.187 --> 14:15.563
♪ Got no time
to think about it ♪

14:15.563 --> 14:16.898
♪ Ain't no other way around it ♪

14:16.898 --> 14:18.232
♪ They can just
forget about it ♪

14:18.232 --> 14:20.318
[ Groans ]

14:20.318 --> 14:22.403
Control, 7015.

14:22.403 --> 14:23.738
Pull an R. A. unit.

14:23.738 --> 14:27.992
We got a drug‐addled victim,
unconscious but breathing.

14:27.992 --> 14:31.996
♪ Run ♪

14:31.996 --> 14:33.581
Hey.

14:33.581 --> 14:35.792
You.

14:35.792 --> 14:37.919
You're that guy.
[ Chuckles ]

14:37.919 --> 14:41.589
Yo, man, come here.
Officer, I need some help.

14:41.589 --> 14:43.925
You need something?
That uniform threw me off.

14:43.925 --> 14:46.260
You're that guy
that got railroaded in France

14:46.260 --> 14:47.553
for killing your buddy.

14:47.553 --> 14:49.931
Hold on. Slow down.
Easy. Come on.

14:51.474 --> 14:52.934
I really do
need some help.

14:55.812 --> 14:57.313
I'm dying of thirst.

14:59.315 --> 15:01.484
Cruel and unusual,
know what I'm saying?

15:03.945 --> 15:06.739
Thank you.

15:06.739 --> 15:07.740
[ Groans ]

15:07.740 --> 15:09.408
[ Slurps ]

15:09.408 --> 15:11.410
[ Exhaling heavily ]

15:11.410 --> 15:13.329
[ Sighs ]

15:13.329 --> 15:15.039
Thought I was done
for sure.

15:15.039 --> 15:16.249
What, the riot?

15:16.249 --> 15:19.418
Yeah. Just another day
in paradise.

15:19.418 --> 15:20.878
You a cop now?

15:23.172 --> 15:24.423
Are you done?

15:24.423 --> 15:27.510
Ah. You and me?

15:27.510 --> 15:28.678
We're the same.

15:28.678 --> 15:30.555
No, man,
not even close.

15:30.555 --> 15:32.140
I'm innocent.

15:32.140 --> 15:34.183
You killed a cop.

15:34.183 --> 15:36.018
Right.

15:36.018 --> 15:38.646
And you see me,
chained up, tatted,

15:38.646 --> 15:41.566
you figure
I fit the bill.

15:41.566 --> 15:43.484
This isn't who I was.

15:43.484 --> 15:46.445
It's who I had to become
to stay alive.

15:46.445 --> 15:47.989
Yeah.
Yo, hold on.

15:47.989 --> 15:49.907
You could spare me a few moments
of your time, brother.

15:49.907 --> 15:51.450
I'll be outside.

15:54.453 --> 15:56.080
You're sure
that's my Leo?

15:56.080 --> 15:57.540
Sgt. Grey:
Yes, ma'am.

15:57.540 --> 15:59.375
Is he okay?
For now.

15:59.375 --> 16:02.086
We're just trying to make sure
he doesn't hurt himself,

16:02.086 --> 16:03.963
or others.
[ Scoffs ]

16:03.963 --> 16:06.382
So he hasn't
contacted you?

16:06.382 --> 16:10.052
No. He wasn't there this morning
when I got home.

16:10.052 --> 16:12.221
I work graveyard.

16:12.221 --> 16:14.599
I called and texted,
but he never responded.

16:14.599 --> 16:16.100
Is that typical
for your son?

16:16.100 --> 16:19.187
Things have been tough for him
ever since...

16:20.229 --> 16:22.732
Go on.
You can say it.

16:25.276 --> 16:27.028
Since his father passed.

16:27.028 --> 16:29.197
Guy was a deadbeat
while he was alive.

16:29.197 --> 16:30.615
Suddenly now,
he's a superhero.

16:30.615 --> 16:34.076
Brian ‐‐
No, I'm sorry.

16:34.076 --> 16:36.329
I try to do right
by that kid.

16:36.329 --> 16:39.207
We both do,
but he makes it impossible.

16:39.207 --> 16:40.750
He barely talks to us.

16:40.750 --> 16:43.127
He spends all of his time
reading these fantasy books,

16:43.127 --> 16:45.046
playing video games.

16:46.005 --> 16:48.507
Did manage to get himself
kicked out of school.

16:48.507 --> 16:50.760
Leo's not in school?

16:50.760 --> 16:53.930
I teach him at home.

16:53.930 --> 16:59.101
It's ‐‐ It's just hard,
uh, with my hours.

16:59.101 --> 17:00.186
♪♪

17:00.186 --> 17:02.605
[ Exhales sharply ]

17:02.605 --> 17:04.190
I'm always tired.

17:04.190 --> 17:06.192
[ Exhales sharply ]

17:06.192 --> 17:08.778
I can't lose him.

17:08.778 --> 17:11.030
And then after my conviction,
I found out

17:11.030 --> 17:12.573
that there were
two eyewitnesses,

17:12.573 --> 17:14.617
both who said the killer
was a short bald guy

17:14.617 --> 17:16.035
who looked
nothing like me.

17:16.035 --> 17:17.578
Okay. So, where was your lawyer
on all this?

17:17.578 --> 17:19.372
Drunk off his ass.

17:19.372 --> 17:22.166
Court appointed,
and he couldn't give a damn.

17:22.166 --> 17:23.376
Now you see
what I'm saying?

17:23.376 --> 17:24.835
Look, you need to file
for a retrial.

17:24.835 --> 17:26.254
I mean,
that's what I did.

17:26.254 --> 17:28.130
[ Scoffs ] I don't have
your kind of money, my brother,

17:28.130 --> 17:31.384
and I can't get a lawyer
to take me on pro bono.

17:31.384 --> 17:32.843
I'm sorry.

17:32.843 --> 17:34.929
[ Sighs ]
I don't need your sorry,

17:34.929 --> 17:38.391
but I could use
your help.

17:38.391 --> 17:40.977
You did two years for
a crime you didn't commit ‐‐

17:40.977 --> 17:43.354
I'm going on 18.

17:43.354 --> 17:45.064
Nurse Todd: Officer,
you have to wait out here.

17:45.064 --> 17:47.817
Surgery should take an hour.
There's no other exits.

17:53.155 --> 17:54.991
Hey.
Hey.

17:54.991 --> 17:56.450
Is everything okay?
Uh, yeah.

17:56.450 --> 17:58.327
Ultrasound
came back clear.
[ Sighs ]

17:58.327 --> 18:00.079
Doctor thinks that it was
just some heartburn.

18:00.079 --> 18:02.707
So, they're gonna run some
blood tests just to be safe.

18:02.707 --> 18:05.167
He getting his shattered arm
set?

18:05.167 --> 18:07.086
Yeah.

18:07.086 --> 18:08.212
What's wrong?

18:11.215 --> 18:12.800
I think
he could be innocent.

18:12.800 --> 18:14.385
Don't even go there.

18:14.385 --> 18:15.803
Look, he talked to me about
his case, and I think ‐‐

18:15.803 --> 18:17.471
Who told you to talk to him?
That's not your job.

18:17.471 --> 18:19.140
He is a cop killer, okay?

18:19.140 --> 18:22.268
So just shut up
and guard him, okay?

18:22.268 --> 18:24.020
Bulgogi tacos.

18:24.020 --> 18:26.731
I didn't know what style
you liked, so I got two of each.

18:26.731 --> 18:28.733
Kenton, how did
you find these?

18:28.733 --> 18:30.985
I tapped into
the LA assistant hive mind.

18:30.985 --> 18:32.945
The truck was on location
in Santa Clarita

18:32.945 --> 18:34.280
serving a movie crew.

18:34.280 --> 18:36.532
I drove over,
put on my headset,

18:36.532 --> 18:38.409
and walked right up
like I was part of the crew.

18:38.409 --> 18:40.369
So your tacos are courtesy
of the director

18:40.369 --> 18:42.413
of "Murder Dance Party:
Part Three".

18:42.413 --> 18:43.998
Damn, you are good.
Mm‐hmm.

18:43.998 --> 18:46.167
No. I'm the best.

18:46.167 --> 18:47.501
Oh.
Ooh!

18:47.501 --> 18:49.754
Hmm. Cocky, too.
Alright. I like that.

18:49.754 --> 18:54.675
But what I have for you now
is ‐‐ it's next level.

18:54.675 --> 18:56.510
Are you up for it?

18:56.510 --> 18:58.220
Bring it, Detective.

18:58.220 --> 19:02.141
Alright, um, I have been looking
for this doll

19:02.141 --> 19:04.101
that I had when
I was a little girl,

19:04.101 --> 19:05.645
to give to my daughter.

19:05.645 --> 19:07.396
But I can't remember
what it was called,

19:07.396 --> 19:09.732
and I haven't been able to
find it anywhere.

19:09.732 --> 19:12.610
But she was the first doll
that I ever saw

19:12.610 --> 19:15.988
that had hair and skin tone
that was just like mine.

19:15.988 --> 19:19.533
And she had this, um,
French‐sounding name

19:19.533 --> 19:23.996
with a pink parasol ‐‐
or was it yellow?

19:24.872 --> 19:27.458
I'm on it.
Watch me do my thing.

19:27.458 --> 19:29.126
[ Scoffs ] What?

19:29.126 --> 19:31.212
♪♪

19:31.212 --> 19:33.089
Here.
I‐I can't have these.

19:33.089 --> 19:40.137
♪♪

19:40.137 --> 19:43.140
Hey.
So, Grey talked to Leo's mom.

19:43.140 --> 19:45.184
His home life
sounds like a real mess.

19:45.184 --> 19:48.479
His parents aren't divorced.
His father died two years ago.

19:48.479 --> 19:50.731
That's rough.
Hey. Here's
the weird thing ‐‐

19:50.731 --> 19:53.109
he's been homeschooled
for over a year.

19:53.109 --> 19:54.652
So he was making up
that whole story

19:54.652 --> 19:56.696
about the princess classmate
who OD'd?

19:56.696 --> 19:58.781
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]
I don't know.

20:00.074 --> 20:02.618
Okay, Leo.
Quest one complete.

20:02.618 --> 20:05.413
How about we call this a victory
and you land?

20:05.413 --> 20:08.708
The hero's journey never ends
after the first quest.

20:08.708 --> 20:09.959
[ Sighs ]

20:09.959 --> 20:11.669
I was afraid you'd say that.
What's next?

20:11.669 --> 20:14.422
You're a gamer. You know
it's not all easy stuff.

20:14.422 --> 20:16.090
Eventually you get to
a boss battle.

20:16.090 --> 20:18.217
<i>A great beast you will struggle</i>
<i>to defeat.</i>

20:18.217 --> 20:20.094
Leo, how about we cut out
the windup

20:20.094 --> 20:21.887
and you just go straight
for the pitch?

20:21.887 --> 20:23.973
How do you feel about
alligators?

20:23.973 --> 20:28.018
♪♪

20:28.018 --> 20:29.562
Hey.
Thanks for coming in.
Yeah.

20:29.562 --> 20:31.230
I just want to verify
a few things.
Mm‐hmm.

20:31.230 --> 20:34.400
Uh, Dez Robinson ‐‐ he works
for you, is that correct?

20:34.400 --> 20:35.901
From time to time.
Yeah.

20:35.901 --> 20:38.612
Okay. He said he worked
two nights ago.

20:38.612 --> 20:40.489
Yeah,
sounds about right.

20:40.489 --> 20:43.367
We had a construction job
down in Hawthorne.

20:43.367 --> 20:45.327
Picked up the night shift
for a few extra bucks.

20:45.327 --> 20:48.456
Any chance he checked
in and then maybe ducked
out for a few hours?

20:48.456 --> 20:51.000
Nah, I was there.
I would've seen that.

20:51.000 --> 20:52.877
You sure?

20:52.877 --> 20:56.922
Because, uh, Dez is suspected
in a triple murder

20:56.922 --> 20:59.133
that happened that night,
so anyone who helps him

20:59.133 --> 21:00.968
would be considered
an accessory.

21:00.968 --> 21:03.137
Hey. Hold on.

21:03.137 --> 21:04.305
I had no idea about that.

21:04.305 --> 21:06.098
I want no parts of that,
alright?

21:06.098 --> 21:07.641
I thought he was just out here
cheating on his girlfriend.

21:07.641 --> 21:09.310
I didn't know he was out here
killing people.

21:09.310 --> 21:10.811
Does that mean you want to
amend your statement?

21:10.811 --> 21:13.314
Hell yeah.
I'm gonna amend my statement.

21:13.314 --> 21:16.150
Dez paid me 500 bucks
to clock him in

21:16.150 --> 21:17.860
on the nights
that he needed an alibi.

21:17.860 --> 21:20.362
Okay. So, to be clear,
Dez did <i>not</i> show up to work

21:20.362 --> 21:21.947
two nights ago?
Right.

21:21.947 --> 21:25.951
Oh, and...
he paid me yesterday

21:25.951 --> 21:27.745
to clock him in
for tonight.

21:27.745 --> 21:29.246
♪♪

21:29.246 --> 21:31.499
Hey. Dez's alibi
fell apart.

21:31.499 --> 21:32.958
Nice work.
So when his lawyer lands,

21:32.958 --> 21:34.585
here's the plan ‐‐
We don't have time
for a plan.

21:34.585 --> 21:36.253
The crew has another target
lined up for tonight.

21:36.253 --> 21:37.505
If we don't figure out
where they're hitting,

21:37.505 --> 21:38.589
they're gonna drop
more bodies.

21:43.344 --> 21:44.929
[ Rattling, door slams ]

21:44.929 --> 21:46.430
Let's never
do that again.

21:46.430 --> 21:48.015
You're gonna need
a much bigger leash than that.

21:48.015 --> 21:50.851
And tranquilizers, lot ‐‐
lots of tranquilizers.

21:50.851 --> 21:52.520
Cupcake is a sweetheart.

21:52.520 --> 21:55.397
Cupcake ate my Taser.

21:55.397 --> 21:57.274
Thank you.
Okay, Leo.

21:57.274 --> 21:59.443
Quest two is complete.
Funny coincidence ‐‐

21:59.443 --> 22:03.280
aside from a reptile
straight out of "Jurassic Park",

22:03.280 --> 22:05.407
we found a bunch of fentanyl
in the house.

22:05.407 --> 22:08.244
Two quests.
Two drug arrests.

22:08.244 --> 22:09.787
We're starting to sense
a pattern here.

22:09.787 --> 22:11.872
Alligator guy had drugs?

22:11.872 --> 22:13.624
It's a good thing
you caught him.

22:13.624 --> 22:15.960
Do you wanna tell us what these
quests are really about?

22:15.960 --> 22:17.545
Not right now.
Leo ‐‐

22:17.545 --> 22:19.547
Relax. You'll get
your third quest soon enough.

22:19.547 --> 22:23.676
♪♪

22:23.676 --> 22:26.095
[ Radio chatter ]

22:29.098 --> 22:31.725
Officer Webb.
Find anything?

22:31.725 --> 22:33.644
The stuff of nightmares.

22:33.644 --> 22:35.229
Man lives like a pig.

22:35.229 --> 22:36.647
So no gun?

22:36.647 --> 22:37.940
Nah.

22:37.940 --> 22:39.316
We need more leverage.

22:39.316 --> 22:40.609
Something
that ties this guy

22:40.609 --> 22:42.152
definitively to the home
invasions.

22:42.152 --> 22:45.447
The only way we stop this crew
in time is if Dez flips.

22:45.447 --> 22:46.532
What have you searched
so far?

22:46.532 --> 22:48.117
We're going full
DEAR system.

22:48.117 --> 22:49.785
You're off
to a good start.

22:49.785 --> 22:51.787
Eliminating things
we don't have to search again.

22:51.787 --> 22:53.539
What's next?

22:53.539 --> 22:54.790
You know
what F. S. T. s are?

22:54.790 --> 22:56.375
Yeah,
Field Sobriety Tests.

22:56.375 --> 22:57.793
Yeah,
and when searching a house,

22:57.793 --> 22:59.420
F.S.T. stands for
something else.

22:59.420 --> 23:01.171
First, you get all the guys
from the outside

23:01.171 --> 23:03.340
to come search inside,
and vice versa.

23:03.340 --> 23:05.009
Fresh set of eyes.

23:05.009 --> 23:06.218
Alright?

23:06.218 --> 23:08.012
L‐100, I need all units
from the outside

23:08.012 --> 23:10.097
to come inside
for a sec.

23:10.097 --> 23:11.807
Then you do
a Systematic grid search.

23:11.807 --> 23:13.684
Ah. So Systematic search
is the "S."

23:13.684 --> 23:16.270
What's the "T"?

23:16.270 --> 23:17.605
Alright, everyone,
listen up.

23:17.605 --> 23:19.356
I want everyone
who was searching outside

23:19.356 --> 23:21.191
to swap with people
on the inside.

23:21.191 --> 23:22.860
Then I want
a three‐foot search grid.

23:22.860 --> 23:24.695
And there's
a $100 gift card

23:24.695 --> 23:26.488
for the first officer
who finds evidence

23:26.488 --> 23:28.032
linking this guy to
our 2‐11.

23:28.032 --> 23:29.825
Got it?
Alright, let's go!

23:29.825 --> 23:31.785
♪♪

23:31.785 --> 23:33.829
The "T" is for
Treat it like a contest.

23:33.829 --> 23:36.248
Cops love to compete,
and they'll push themselves

23:36.248 --> 23:38.000
even harder if they know
there's something to win.

23:39.418 --> 23:41.629
<i>[ Woman speaking indistinctly</i>
<i>over P. A. ]</i>

23:44.340 --> 23:45.507
What are you doing here?

23:45.507 --> 23:48.802
Um, why didn't you tell me
you were seeing your OB?

23:48.802 --> 23:51.388
I‐I didn't want to worry you
if it was nothing,

23:51.388 --> 23:52.473
and ‐‐ and it was.

23:52.473 --> 23:54.308
It was just a little
aggressive heartburn.

23:54.308 --> 23:55.517
I don't care.

23:55.517 --> 23:57.436
If you burp funny,
I wanna know.

24:00.940 --> 24:02.524
He called you here,
didn't he?

24:02.524 --> 24:03.817
And it wasn't about me.

24:03.817 --> 24:06.695
Yes, ma'am. I, um ‐‐
I called them about Langston.

24:08.447 --> 24:13.869
Are you trying to get everyone
in the LAPD to hate you?

24:13.869 --> 24:15.704
Because that is
what is gonna happen

24:15.704 --> 24:18.582
if you advocate
for a convicted cop killer.

24:18.582 --> 24:20.709
I told you to drop this.

24:20.709 --> 24:23.712
All due respect, if there is
even a sliver of a chance

24:23.712 --> 24:25.673
that he is innocent,
it needs to be investigated.

24:25.673 --> 24:28.175
Yeah, look.
That hardcore dude in there

24:28.175 --> 24:31.053
is unrecognizable from the guy
that went in 18 years ago.

24:31.053 --> 24:33.806
He's been institutionalized.
I've seen it a thousand times.

24:35.891 --> 24:39.186
A nice haircut and a cute smile
does not mean he is innocent.

24:39.186 --> 24:41.397
Yeah, and a conviction doesn't
mean that he's guilty, either.

24:41.397 --> 24:43.482
I mean, I'm proof of that.
[ Sighs ]

24:43.482 --> 24:44.650
If I'd have stayed
in prison,

24:44.650 --> 24:46.068
that's how
I would've ended up.

24:46.068 --> 24:47.569
And now that I have
a platform

24:47.569 --> 24:48.988
to help people
who are wrongfully accused,

24:48.988 --> 24:50.197
I mean, I have to use it.

24:50.197 --> 24:52.908
I thought you were trying to
"rebrand" yourself.

24:52.908 --> 24:54.994
To ‐‐ To reclaim
your identity

24:54.994 --> 24:56.912
separate from
your conviction.

24:56.912 --> 24:59.999
If you tie yourself to Langston,
you will undo all of that.

24:59.999 --> 25:01.834
Alright, look,
there is no reason

25:01.834 --> 25:03.460
to go right to
the worst‐case scenario.

25:03.460 --> 25:05.462
Let James and I
talk to him,

25:05.462 --> 25:07.589
just see what kind of
impression we get.

25:07.589 --> 25:09.717
Just to see
if there's any merit.

25:14.138 --> 25:16.223
Alright.
You got 15 minutes.

25:16.223 --> 25:17.641
Okay.

25:20.686 --> 25:22.438
[ Door closes ]

25:22.438 --> 25:23.605
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

25:23.605 --> 25:25.274
Still waiting on
that third quest, Leo.

25:25.274 --> 25:28.986
Unless you want to just skip it
and land?

25:28.986 --> 25:30.529
You still up there, Leo?

25:30.529 --> 25:33.782
Yeah. Yeah, I'm here,
just enjoying the view.

25:33.782 --> 25:35.284
It's peaceful up here.

25:35.284 --> 25:36.368
You know, we did
a little digging

25:36.368 --> 25:38.037
after our last conversation.

25:38.037 --> 25:39.788
Turns out Murray,
the guy with the alligator,

25:39.788 --> 25:42.833
one of his known associates
is Brian Johst,

25:42.833 --> 25:44.334
your mom's boyfriend.

25:44.334 --> 25:45.669
<i>I'm guessing they have</i>
<i>a little</i>

25:45.669 --> 25:47.337
distribution racket
running?

25:47.337 --> 25:48.839
Yeah, and we'd bet money

25:48.839 --> 25:50.424
that one of the dealers
they sell to

25:50.424 --> 25:53.302
is the guy we arrested
in Quest One.

25:53.302 --> 25:55.512
That's quite an epic tale.

25:55.512 --> 25:59.308
Let's cut out this fantasy crap,
shall we, Leo?

25:59.308 --> 26:01.351
We know you didn't send us
to that house

26:01.351 --> 26:03.437
to avenge a classmate.
There is no classmate.

26:03.437 --> 26:07.149
But I think there is a princess
you need us to save.

26:07.149 --> 26:10.527
Your mom ‐‐ she has
a history of drug abuse,

26:10.527 --> 26:12.654
but it seems like
she'd been clean for a while?

26:14.573 --> 26:17.493
She relapsed
after my dad died.

26:17.493 --> 26:20.037
Then she rallied,
got herself clean.

26:20.037 --> 26:22.706
It was good,
like before.

26:24.750 --> 26:26.710
Then she met Brian.

26:26.710 --> 26:29.797
You have to get her
away from him.

26:29.797 --> 26:33.008
He's killing her.

26:33.008 --> 26:35.427
That's your third quest.
Leo out.

26:37.179 --> 26:39.473
We have no evidence
tying Brian to the fentanyl.

26:39.473 --> 26:40.724
We can't arrest him.

26:40.724 --> 26:43.143
And Leo's got 40 minutes
before he runs out of fuel.

26:43.143 --> 26:45.813
[ Dramatic music plays ]

26:50.067 --> 26:51.527
[ Cellphone ringing ]
Yeah.

26:51.527 --> 26:52.986
Tell me
you found something.

26:52.986 --> 26:55.614
Some old gloves, possible
burglary tools, impact weapons.

26:55.614 --> 26:57.282
Nothing that's gonna help us.
What's going on?

26:57.282 --> 26:58.951
Dez is about to walk out of here
with his lawyer.

26:58.951 --> 27:00.202
Right now,
all I can charge him with

27:00.202 --> 27:01.912
is possession
of stolen property.

27:01.912 --> 27:04.373
Can you stall them?
20 minutes.

27:04.373 --> 27:05.874
Webb: Sorry, Sarge.
[ Cellphone beeps ]

27:05.874 --> 27:07.167
We've turned this place
upside down.

27:07.167 --> 27:09.711
These tools here
are all we could find.

27:09.711 --> 27:12.005
'Cause you're only human.
Excuse me?

27:12.005 --> 27:15.092
L‐100, I need 8706
at my location, Code 3.

27:15.092 --> 27:16.552
Dispatch: <i>Copy that.</i>
8706?

27:16.552 --> 27:17.761
Uh, why the hell
do we need him here?

27:17.761 --> 27:19.054
You'll see.

27:19.054 --> 27:21.181
Okay, taking your statement
into consideration...

27:21.181 --> 27:24.518
And the few online articles that
we read about your case ‐‐

27:24.518 --> 27:28.105
Come on, just ‐‐ you can just
tell me straight.

27:28.105 --> 27:31.108
Can you get me outta here?
Way too early to tell.

27:31.108 --> 27:32.818
But what I've read has
definitely triggered

27:32.818 --> 27:33.902
some alarms.

27:33.902 --> 27:35.404
I mean, it's clear
there were several

27:35.404 --> 27:37.114
investigative discrepancies,
and clearly,

27:37.114 --> 27:39.116
you were not given
adequate counsel.

27:39.116 --> 27:41.743
So what do I do?
Wesley:
Let me make some calls.

27:41.743 --> 27:44.079
There are a few lawyers I would
trust to take your case.

27:44.079 --> 27:45.622
Pro bono?
Pro bono.

27:45.622 --> 27:48.667
[ Chuckles ]
That's great.

27:48.667 --> 27:50.752
James: But there are
no guarantees here, okay?

27:50.752 --> 27:53.964
There's no promises,
just a little hope.

27:53.964 --> 27:55.382
That's all I can handle.

27:55.382 --> 27:57.801
This will be the hardest fight
of your life.

27:57.801 --> 28:00.304
I'm ready.

28:00.304 --> 28:02.723
I appreciate you both.

28:05.100 --> 28:06.059
You.

28:06.059 --> 28:09.396
♪♪

28:09.396 --> 28:11.857
You listened.

28:11.857 --> 28:13.984
♪♪

28:13.984 --> 28:16.486
It's been a long time since
anybody's done that.

28:16.486 --> 28:18.322
♪♪

28:18.322 --> 28:19.114
Thank you.

28:19.114 --> 28:22.367
♪♪

28:22.367 --> 28:24.369
See, bomb sniffing dogs
don't look for bombs,

28:24.369 --> 28:25.454
they look for bomb ingredients,

28:25.454 --> 28:27.247
like gunpowder
from an illegal firearm.

28:27.247 --> 28:29.791
♪♪

28:29.791 --> 28:32.461
Come on, boy, you got this.

28:32.461 --> 28:34.630
[ Thor barking ]

28:34.630 --> 28:35.797
Are you kidding me?

28:35.797 --> 28:38.008
Did you really just get
distracted by a squirrel?

28:38.008 --> 28:40.802
[ Thor barks ]
Do you realize
how clichéd that is?

28:40.802 --> 28:42.763
[ Thor sniffing ]

28:42.763 --> 28:46.099
♪♪

28:46.099 --> 28:47.935
He found something.

28:47.935 --> 28:50.479
[ Knocking ]

28:50.479 --> 28:56.360
♪♪

28:56.360 --> 28:57.152
Okay.

28:57.152 --> 28:58.820
Got him.

29:01.323 --> 29:03.533
Oh, hey,
you just missed James.

29:03.533 --> 29:04.826
He and Wesley went down
to the cafeteria

29:04.826 --> 29:06.036
to make some calls.

29:06.036 --> 29:08.538
They're gonna get Langston
an attorney.

29:08.538 --> 29:10.666
[ Sighs ] I'll text them
and tell them

29:10.666 --> 29:12.626
not to waste their time,
'cause a retrial

29:12.626 --> 29:14.628
isn't gonna matter.
Why?

29:14.628 --> 29:16.797
Sheriff's Department combed
through security footage

29:16.797 --> 29:18.131
from the prison riot.

29:18.131 --> 29:20.884
Your innocent man here
stomped a guard.

29:20.884 --> 29:22.803
[ Sighs ]

29:22.803 --> 29:24.221
Is he okay?
No.

29:24.221 --> 29:25.973
He is paralyzed
from the waist down.

29:25.973 --> 29:27.557
[ Sighs ]
They are charging Langston

29:27.557 --> 29:29.643
with attempted murder
of a peace officer.

29:29.643 --> 29:31.061
That's a 20‐to‐life
sentence.

29:31.061 --> 29:33.772
Which is why a retrial
is pointless.

29:33.772 --> 29:36.191
He's not getting out
of prison.

29:36.191 --> 29:38.610
[ Scoffs ]

29:38.610 --> 29:40.696
Yo, this system is a joke.

29:40.696 --> 29:42.864
I mean, if Langston wasn't
wrongfully convicted

29:42.864 --> 29:44.157
in the first place,
he wouldn't have spent

29:44.157 --> 29:46.201
half his life stuck in prison,
wouldn't have been caught up

29:46.201 --> 29:48.662
in that riot, thinking
the only way to survive
was to stomp a guard.

29:48.662 --> 29:51.289
♪♪

29:51.289 --> 29:52.874
What are you doing?

29:54.876 --> 29:57.546
I'm gonna tell him
that it's over.

29:57.546 --> 30:02.634
♪♪

30:02.634 --> 30:03.510
[ Door closes ]

30:03.510 --> 30:06.388
[ Door buzzes, opens ]

30:06.388 --> 30:09.182
How's Cupcake?

30:09.182 --> 30:11.852
The alligator?
Yeah.

30:11.852 --> 30:13.061
Fine.

30:13.061 --> 30:16.898
You, on the other hand,
are screwed, my friend.

30:16.898 --> 30:19.443
My officers found a stockpile of
fentanyl in your house.

30:19.443 --> 30:21.737
Where'd you get it?
H‐Has she seen a vet yet?

30:21.737 --> 30:23.947
They ‐‐
She swallowed a Taser.

30:23.947 --> 30:27.492
Hey, you are in a lot of
trouble, Murray.

30:27.492 --> 30:29.578
You need to focus
on the drugs.

30:29.578 --> 30:32.497
Now, we know you've been selling
to high school kids.

30:32.497 --> 30:34.332
Who are you working with?
No one, man.

30:34.332 --> 30:36.418
Look, this is
important, okay?

30:36.418 --> 30:38.545
Cupcake has
a very specific diet.

30:38.545 --> 30:40.630
I‐I can write it down
for you.

30:43.633 --> 30:46.136
Okay, I'll do you
one better.

30:46.136 --> 30:49.389
I'll let you talk to the people
taking care of Cupcake

30:49.389 --> 30:50.724
and make sure
she's all right.
[ Gasps ]

30:50.724 --> 30:54.061
But first, you need to
name your accomplices.

30:54.061 --> 30:55.937
Deal.

30:55.937 --> 30:57.773
[ Indistinct conversations ]

30:57.773 --> 30:58.774
Okay.

30:58.774 --> 30:59.775
Sgt. Grey:
<i>Murray flipped.</i>

30:59.775 --> 31:01.193
<i>We got a warrant</i>
<i>on Brian Johst.</i>

31:01.193 --> 31:03.028
<i>You want to serve it?</i>
Yes, sir.

31:03.028 --> 31:04.488
Thank you very much.

31:04.488 --> 31:06.406
♪♪

31:06.406 --> 31:11.328
Attention, Airship Three,
I have a quest for <i>you.</i>

31:11.328 --> 31:13.663
[ Chuckles ]

31:13.663 --> 31:14.748
What is it?

31:14.748 --> 31:16.291
Can you see your house
from up there?

31:16.291 --> 31:18.001
Hold on.

31:18.001 --> 31:24.049
♪♪

31:24.049 --> 31:25.967
Thank you very much.
Come on, let's go.

31:25.967 --> 31:28.929
♪♪

31:28.929 --> 31:30.931
Hey, Young Hero,
are you seeing this?

31:30.931 --> 31:32.099
Every second.

31:32.099 --> 31:33.517
Great.
The quest is over.

31:33.517 --> 31:34.810
I think it's time
to come down now.

31:34.810 --> 31:36.978
Oh, thank God,
'cause I have been air‐sick

31:36.978 --> 31:38.647
for the past three hours,
and I ‐‐

31:38.647 --> 31:39.731
[ Alarm blaring ]

31:39.731 --> 31:41.983
Uh‐oh.

31:41.983 --> 31:43.193
What? What's wrong?

31:43.193 --> 31:44.486
I'm out of gas.

31:44.486 --> 31:46.988
[ Alarm blaring ]

31:52.160 --> 31:54.162
[ Engine sputtering ]

31:54.162 --> 31:57.666
[ Siren wailing ]

31:57.666 --> 32:02.712
♪♪

32:02.712 --> 32:04.297
Leo: Come on, come on.

32:04.297 --> 32:05.632
Nolan: Yes.

32:05.632 --> 32:08.343
[ Helicopter powering down ]

32:14.141 --> 32:16.184
That was ‐‐ Oh, wow.

32:16.184 --> 32:18.145
Hi. Hey.
Hey, hey, hey, hey.

32:18.145 --> 32:20.397
Hey.
That was, uh...
[ Chuckles ]

32:20.397 --> 32:22.440
That was intense.
Never do that again.

32:22.440 --> 32:24.276
[ Sirens wailing ]
Yeah, the, um,

32:24.276 --> 32:27.487
hero's journey is over.
[ Chuckles ]

32:27.487 --> 32:29.197
Oh.
Not yet.

32:29.197 --> 32:31.867
[ Sirens stop ]

32:31.867 --> 32:35.620
What?
You stole
a police helicopter, Leo.

32:35.620 --> 32:37.330
You're under arrest.

32:39.541 --> 32:41.126
[ Handcuffs jingle ]

32:44.588 --> 32:45.922
[ Handcuffs click ]

32:45.922 --> 32:47.340
♪♪

32:47.340 --> 32:48.508
What'd he give us?
Everything.

32:48.508 --> 32:49.926
Every job, every guy
on his crew.

32:49.926 --> 32:51.178
And the location
of tonight's robbery?

32:51.178 --> 32:52.220
Yeah, and they're supposed to
hit the house

32:52.220 --> 32:53.555
within the hour.

32:53.555 --> 33:00.896
♪♪

33:00.896 --> 33:02.397
[ Cellphone clicking ]

33:02.397 --> 33:08.486
♪♪

33:08.486 --> 33:10.739
Give me the keys
and phone.

33:10.739 --> 33:12.449
[ Keys rattle ]

33:12.449 --> 33:14.618
You know, nobody takes pride
in their work anymore.

33:14.618 --> 33:15.911
Used to be
a getaway driver

33:15.911 --> 33:17.495
was hyper‐alert
during a robbery.

33:17.495 --> 33:19.080
I blame social media.

33:19.080 --> 33:20.498
Look, I don't know
what this is about,

33:20.498 --> 33:21.791
but you got
the wrong guy.

33:21.791 --> 33:23.084
No, we don't.
Dez told us

33:23.084 --> 33:24.961
you'd be parked right here,
keeping a look‐out.

33:24.961 --> 33:27.380
He also said there's three guys
inside robbing the place.

33:27.380 --> 33:29.257
Is he right?
Is there three men inside?

33:31.051 --> 33:32.677
Answer quick, because if they
start killing people,

33:32.677 --> 33:34.971
those murders are on you.

33:34.971 --> 33:36.348
Yeah.

33:36.348 --> 33:40.268
It's three guys, supposed to be
in and out in 30 minutes,

33:40.268 --> 33:41.561
and they're 28 minutes in.

33:41.561 --> 33:42.812
So, what was
the plan going in?

33:42.812 --> 33:44.981
Where are
we gonna find 'em?

33:44.981 --> 33:46.441
Master bedroom's upstairs.

33:46.441 --> 33:48.818
That's where the safe is.
Don cracks the safe

33:48.818 --> 33:51.196
while Terry loots
the rest of the bedrooms.

33:51.196 --> 33:54.699
Stosh's job is to keep a gun on
the family downstairs.

33:54.699 --> 33:55.575
Get out.

33:57.327 --> 33:59.663
Come on.
Go that way.

33:59.663 --> 34:01.331
♪♪

34:01.331 --> 34:02.707
[ Handcuffs clink ]

34:02.707 --> 34:04.417
[ Sighs ]

34:04.417 --> 34:06.253
We can't go in hot
with a guy hovering

34:06.253 --> 34:08.255
over the family
with a weapon.

34:08.255 --> 34:10.966
So we go in
a different way.

34:10.966 --> 34:19.849
♪♪

34:19.849 --> 34:21.226
Alpha team set.

34:21.226 --> 34:27.023
♪♪

34:27.023 --> 34:32.821
♪♪

34:32.821 --> 34:34.030
[ Knock on door ]

34:34.030 --> 34:39.202
♪♪

34:39.202 --> 34:41.329
Someone's here.

34:41.329 --> 34:42.998
[ Doorbell rings ]

34:42.998 --> 34:44.833
[ Cellphone clicking ]

34:44.833 --> 34:46.376
♪♪

34:46.376 --> 34:47.544
[ Cellphone chimes ]

34:47.544 --> 34:49.921
♪♪

34:49.921 --> 34:51.881
[ Cellphone chimes ]

34:51.881 --> 34:54.301
Delivery guy.
I'll get rid of him.

34:54.301 --> 34:55.969
[ Doorbell rings ]

34:55.969 --> 34:57.804
We didn't order anything!
Go away!

34:57.804 --> 35:01.308
[ Glass shatters, explosion ]

35:01.308 --> 35:03.643
‐Get down! Get down!
‐Get down on the ground!

35:03.643 --> 35:05.228
Man: Don't move.
[ Handcuffs click ]

35:05.228 --> 35:07.355
Man #2: Clear!

35:07.355 --> 35:08.607
‐All clear!
‐Clear!

35:08.607 --> 35:10.567
Hostages secure.

35:10.567 --> 35:14.613
♪♪

35:14.613 --> 35:18.283
[ Gunshots, glass shattering ]

35:18.283 --> 35:20.910
♪♪

35:20.910 --> 35:22.162
Ugh!

35:23.371 --> 35:24.581
Give me a bang!

35:27.709 --> 35:29.419
[ Flash bang explodes ]
Ugh!

35:29.419 --> 35:34.090
♪♪

35:34.090 --> 35:38.720
♪♪

35:38.720 --> 35:40.347
[ Grunts ]

35:40.347 --> 35:42.891
♪♪

35:42.891 --> 35:44.351
[ Gunshots ]

35:46.353 --> 35:49.522
[ Groaning ]

35:49.522 --> 35:51.775
[ Grunting ]

35:51.775 --> 35:57.739
♪♪

35:57.739 --> 35:59.240
[ Groaning ]

35:59.240 --> 36:00.909
[ Bone cracks ]
[ Screams ]

36:00.909 --> 36:03.578
[ Both grunting ]

36:03.578 --> 36:06.331
[ Handcuffs clicking ]

36:06.331 --> 36:07.624
You okay?

36:07.624 --> 36:09.584
[ Exhales heavily ]
You know it.

36:14.381 --> 36:15.715
Hey.
Sheriff Department's here

36:15.715 --> 36:17.258
to transport Langston
back to prison.

36:17.258 --> 36:18.593
So we're free to go,
if you're ready.

36:18.593 --> 36:20.470
I am.
Bloodwork came back clear.

36:20.470 --> 36:22.472
[ Elevator dings ]
That's great news.

36:22.472 --> 36:24.391
No way!

36:24.391 --> 36:25.892
Told you
I was no joke.

36:25.892 --> 36:28.228
What?! I have not seen one of
these since I was 10.

36:28.228 --> 36:30.105
Wh‐Where did you
find this?

36:30.105 --> 36:31.523
You can get anything
on the dark web.

36:31.523 --> 36:33.274
Wow. Thank you.

36:33.274 --> 36:34.943
[ Chuckles ] You really are
the best assistant ever.

36:34.943 --> 36:37.278
[ Laughs ]
You don't lose him.

36:37.278 --> 36:40.615
Actually, I have to
tender my resignation.

36:40.615 --> 36:42.033
Hulu just bought
my pilot!

36:42.033 --> 36:44.202
What? That's great.
Congratulations.

36:44.202 --> 36:45.203
Thanks.
Yeah.

36:45.203 --> 36:46.705
Guess I need
my own assistant now.

36:46.705 --> 36:48.832
Good luck
with the show.

36:48.832 --> 36:50.375
And your baby.
Thank you.

36:53.169 --> 36:54.587
Hmm. [ Chuckles ]
Hmm.

36:54.587 --> 36:55.797
Don't touch it.

36:55.797 --> 36:57.173
Hey.

36:57.173 --> 37:00.427
I'll go pull
the shop around.

37:00.427 --> 37:02.429
So everything is fine.

37:02.429 --> 37:04.264
Best bloodwork
she's ever seen.

37:04.264 --> 37:06.182
I knew it would be.

37:06.182 --> 37:08.143
Listen, I‐I am sorry.

37:08.143 --> 37:09.811
I should've
called you earlier.

37:09.811 --> 37:13.314
But to tell you the truth,
I was terrified.

37:13.314 --> 37:15.191
And I needed to pretend
that it was nothing

37:15.191 --> 37:18.319
and if I called you,
I would have to admit

37:18.319 --> 37:20.822
that it could be something.

37:20.822 --> 37:22.532
And I‐I get that,

37:22.532 --> 37:26.369
but you shouldn't deal
with these things alone.

37:26.369 --> 37:29.038
Look, trust me,
fear is the worst thing

37:29.038 --> 37:30.790
to have to go through
by yourself.

37:30.790 --> 37:31.958
Uh...
[ Chuckles ]

37:31.958 --> 37:34.794
There's, uh, something
I haven't told you.

37:34.794 --> 37:39.007
Um...I was diagnosed
with placenta previa

37:39.007 --> 37:42.969
when I had Lila,
and I started hemorrhaging

37:42.969 --> 37:44.846
late in the pregnancy.

37:44.846 --> 37:47.140
Which is why you freaked out
about a little heartburn.

37:47.140 --> 37:49.726
I should be happy,
you know,

37:49.726 --> 37:52.729
planning her nursery
and buying clothes,

37:52.729 --> 37:55.607
but I'm just terrified
something's gonna happen.

37:55.607 --> 37:59.027
Maybe we can take this
one day at a time.

37:59.027 --> 38:03.239
You know, whatever, we'll ‐‐
we'll ‐‐ we'll deal with it...

38:03.239 --> 38:04.616
together.

38:04.616 --> 38:06.075
I'm good with that.

38:06.075 --> 38:07.452
[ Arkells' "Strong" plays ]

38:07.452 --> 38:10.246
So, what is the deal
with the creepy old doll?

38:10.246 --> 38:11.414
She's not creepy.

38:11.414 --> 38:13.875
Oh, no. All dolls
are inherently creepy.

38:13.875 --> 38:16.503
Spoken like the father
of two boys.

38:16.503 --> 38:17.545
Here, hold her.

38:17.545 --> 38:20.840
Oh, I‐I really don't want to.
Hold her!

38:20.840 --> 38:24.052
[ Clears throat ]
[ Laughs ]

38:24.052 --> 38:26.679
Look at how cute
this is.

38:26.679 --> 38:27.764
Come on.

38:27.764 --> 38:29.682
Got all your stuff?
Yeah.

38:29.682 --> 38:31.851
And your court summons?
Yeah.

38:31.851 --> 38:34.020
But they took my police ID,
though.

38:34.020 --> 38:35.939
The one you stole
to access the roof?

38:35.939 --> 38:38.149
Not surprised.
Where did you get that, anyway?

38:38.149 --> 38:39.901
I lifted it off some cop.

38:39.901 --> 38:43.071
Uh, S‐S‐Smith? Schmitt?
[ Stammers ]

38:43.071 --> 38:44.280
Smitty?

38:44.280 --> 38:45.907
Yeah.
You know him?

38:45.907 --> 38:47.450
[ Sighing ] Yeah.

38:47.450 --> 38:50.620
Well, look, thank you.

38:50.620 --> 38:51.704
Not a problem.

38:51.704 --> 38:55.333
Listen, if ever
you have a problem,

38:55.333 --> 38:59.045
before you go stealing
any aircraft, just call me.

38:59.045 --> 39:00.755
Just aircrafts?
Any vessel.

39:00.755 --> 39:03.049
Any wheeled vehicle.
Or animal ‐‐

39:03.049 --> 39:05.552
Basically, anything
you could ride in or on.
[ Chuckles ]

39:05.552 --> 39:09.055
Deal. What if I have another
epic quest to go on?

39:09.055 --> 39:10.056
Try the bus.

39:10.056 --> 39:11.724
Okay, yeah.
That makes sense.

39:11.724 --> 39:12.851
♪ Stay strong for me
and I'll stay strong for you ♪

39:12.851 --> 39:15.895
♪ Summer is here
but it's slipping away ♪

39:15.895 --> 39:18.314
♪ Why would we want
to waste a good day? ♪

39:18.314 --> 39:19.941
Okay, I got it.
Yeah.

39:19.941 --> 39:22.110
Yeah, look, so, um,
just give me some time,

39:22.110 --> 39:24.279
and I'll get everything you need
over to you.

39:24.279 --> 39:26.197
Yeah. Hey, look, man,
I‐I really appreciate this,

39:26.197 --> 39:28.283
and so does Mr. Bryant.

39:28.283 --> 39:31.035
Alright. Bye.
What are you doing?

39:31.035 --> 39:33.872
Wesley gave me a name
of a lawyer

39:33.872 --> 39:35.498
willing to take
Langston's case.

39:35.498 --> 39:38.501
Why? I thought we agreed
that it was over for that guy.

39:38.501 --> 39:40.169
He ‐‐ He paralyzed a guard.

39:40.169 --> 39:42.839
Right. And he should
be punished for that.

39:42.839 --> 39:45.508
But he may not have killed
that cop 18 years ago,

39:45.508 --> 39:48.803
and we owe it to that officer's
family to find the truth.

39:48.803 --> 39:50.263
Because if Langston's innocent,
then that means

39:50.263 --> 39:51.931
there's someone out there
right now

39:51.931 --> 39:54.350
who got away with murder.

39:54.350 --> 39:57.186
Who gets to sleep in his bed
every night,

39:57.186 --> 40:01.524
gets to walk out of his front
door a free man every morning.

40:01.524 --> 40:05.653
I can't imagine how hard
it must have been for you.

40:05.653 --> 40:09.824
I was locked in a cell
for 541 days,

40:09.824 --> 40:12.327
in a prison that was built
in the 1800s ‐‐

40:12.327 --> 40:15.204
and, trust me, it hadn't
gotten nicer with age.

40:15.204 --> 40:17.916
My best friend was dead.
I thought my life was over.

40:17.916 --> 40:20.543
But you know what?
I got lucky, I got out,

40:20.543 --> 40:22.128
and I got a second chance.

40:22.128 --> 40:25.340
But the person
who murdered Patrick ‐‐

40:25.340 --> 40:27.300
he's still out there.

40:27.300 --> 40:30.845
And ‐‐ And no one
is looking for him,

40:30.845 --> 40:32.347
because they still think
that I did it.

40:32.347 --> 40:34.349
♪ And I'll stay strong for you ♪

40:34.349 --> 40:41.397
♪♪

40:41.397 --> 40:43.524
You need a little help?

40:43.524 --> 40:45.526
No.
I need lots of help.

40:45.526 --> 40:47.695
I don't ‐‐ I don't know
what I'm doing.

40:47.695 --> 40:49.906
Okay.
Show me what you got.

40:49.906 --> 40:52.617
♪ It's one way how to deal ♪

40:52.617 --> 40:55.370
Hey. Ready to go?

40:55.370 --> 40:57.205
Yeah. Can't wait
to get horizontal.

40:57.205 --> 41:00.291
It's been a long day.

41:00.291 --> 41:01.918
I've been doing
some thinking ‐‐

41:01.918 --> 41:03.419
I've warned you
about that.

41:03.419 --> 41:06.255
I helped Aaron out today,
just looking at a case.

41:06.255 --> 41:07.674
I heard.

41:07.674 --> 41:08.841
You think he's innocent?

41:08.841 --> 41:10.218
Maybe.

41:10.218 --> 41:12.053
I don't know for sure.

41:12.053 --> 41:15.598
You know, what I <i>do</i> know
is he had a terrible lawyer.

41:15.598 --> 41:18.101
I think when I get my license
back, I might want to ‐‐

41:18.101 --> 41:22.105
You want to do even more
pro bono work.

41:22.105 --> 41:23.231
Am I that predictable?

41:23.231 --> 41:24.524
Yes, you are.

41:24.524 --> 41:26.275
I always know you're gonna do
the selfless thing

41:26.275 --> 41:28.444
because that's
the kind of man you are.

41:28.444 --> 41:29.696
And you're okay with that?

41:29.696 --> 41:31.280
Why? Because you're gonna make
even less money?

41:31.280 --> 41:33.074
[ Scoffs ] Why would I have
a problem with that?

41:33.074 --> 41:35.076
[ Chuckles ] Yeah.

41:35.076 --> 41:36.577
[ Chuckles ]

41:36.577 --> 41:38.246
♪♪

41:38.246 --> 41:40.623
Hey. You walked Leo out?

41:40.623 --> 41:42.166
Yeah, just left him
with his mom.

41:42.166 --> 41:44.043
What you got there?

41:44.043 --> 41:45.545
It's for
completing your quests.

41:45.545 --> 41:46.754
[ Laughing ] Hey!

41:46.754 --> 41:48.214
But you completed them
with me.

41:48.214 --> 41:50.383
I know. I made a trophy
for myself, too.

41:50.383 --> 41:52.552
[ Sighs ] Anyone else
have a crazy day?

41:52.552 --> 41:54.887
You have no idea.
You know what?

41:54.887 --> 41:56.389
Let's get changed,
grab a drink.
Yes.

41:56.389 --> 41:57.598
‐On Nolan.
‐Whoa.

41:57.598 --> 41:59.726
We're good for one. Then we need
to spring the nanny.

41:59.726 --> 42:01.769
♪♪

42:01.769 --> 42:02.854
Sorry, hold up.

42:02.854 --> 42:04.689
I'm authorizing
all overtime.

42:04.689 --> 42:07.275
There was an accident
at Animal Control,

42:07.275 --> 42:08.776
and they need
all the help they can get.

42:08.776 --> 42:10.445
What's going on?

42:10.445 --> 42:11.779
Cupcake broke free.

42:12.864 --> 42:13.948
Who's Cupcake?

42:21.956 --> 42:31.215
♪♪

42:31.215 --> 42:40.516
♪♪

42:40.516 --> 42:49.859
♪♪
